<div id="main_content">
	<h2>ACE Fellow to Study UCF Administration, Prepare for Senior Leadership</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Tom Evelyn
		
		<span class="date">Oct. 11, 2004</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE83/en_US/040929AwildaHamilton.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Kelly Petrik</p>
			
			<p></p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=00240041c425b20ff4cc08517007aa0">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:tevelyn@mail.ucf.edu">Tom Evelyn</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-5988</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.acenet.edu/">American Council on Education</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Awilda Hamilton, an associate dean at <place /><placename />Kent</placename /> <placename />State</placename /> <placetype />University</placetype /></place />, will spend a year at the <place /><placetype />University</placetype /> of <placename />Central Florida</placename /></place /> learning about its administration and preparing for a senior leadership role at her home university, UCF Provost Terry Hickey announced.</p><p /><p /><p>Starting this fall, <city /><place />Hamilton</place /></city /> will serve as an ACE Fellow. The program was created by the American Council on Education to improve leadership in higher education by identifying and preparing promising faculty and administrators for senior administrative roles.</p><p>My hope is to have a better sense of what I want to do next, roles that I want to pursue, <city /><place />Hamilton</place /></city /> said. And the expectation is that Ill leave here having contributed something.</p><p /><p /><p>ACE Fellows focus on issues of concern to their home universities while working with presidents and other senior officers at their host schools. The fellows, who are nominated by their presidents or chancellors and selected in a national competition, are included in the highest levels of decision-making. They also participate in administrative activities and work on specific issues or projects.</p><p /><p /><p>Hamilton</place /></city /> said she plans to study the systemic elements of the organization that impact communication and collaboration. She is also interested in studying the change process and how it affects an institution. </p><p /><p /><p>It should be embraced and celebrated, <city /><place />Hamilton</place /></city /> said. Im getting proficient at watching feet: Its not what you say, its what you do.</p><p /><p /><p>Hamilton</place /></city /> has served as the associate dean for Academic Affairs in the College and Graduate School of Education at <place /><placename />Kent</placename /> <placename />State</placename /> <placetype />University</placetype /></place /> since 2001. In that role she is responsible for graduate education and program development, evaluation, and advocacy for the college.</p><p /><p /><p>She previously served at <place /><placename />Kent</placename /> <placename />State</placename /></place /> as the coordinator of Elementary Education in the Department of Teacher Development and Curriculum Studies and as director of the Teaching Leadership Consortium Project.</p><p /><p /><p>Before coming to <place /><placename />Kent</placename /> <placename />State</placename /></place />, <city /><place />Hamilton</place /></city /> worked as a principal and central office administrator at school districts in the <city /><place />Cleveland</place /></city /> area.</p><p /><p /><p>Hamilton</place /></city /> has a bachelors degree in microbiology from <place /><placename />Howard</placename /> <placename />University</placename /></place />. She earned a masters degree in elementary education from <place /><placename />Ohio</placename /> <placetype />University</placetype /></place /> and a doctorate in educational administration from the <place /><placetype />University</placetype /> of <placename />Akron</placename /></place />.</p><p /><p /><p>Everything is brand-new to me, <city /><place />Hamilton</place /></city /> said of moving away from <state /><place />Ohio</place /></state /> for the program. Im going to be challenged because I have to work outside of my comfort zone. Thats my charge.</p><p /><p /><p>Most of the previous ACE fellows have advanced into major positions in academic administration, said Marlene Ross, director of the program. Of the more than 1,400 fellows who have come through the program since it started 39 years ago, more than 1,300 have become provosts, vice presidents or deans and more than 250 have become presidents or chancellors.</p><p /><p /><p>The individual selected must have demonstrated strong leadership ability, Ross said. The Fellows Program will sharpen and enhance their leadership skills and prepare them to address issues of concern to the higher education community.</p><p /><p /><p>Founded in 1918, ACE is the nations largest higher education association, representing more then 1,600 college and university presidents and more than 200 related associations nationwide.</p>
		
	
